⸻

Minimal Prompting Rules

For implementation, the engine prompt should enforce:
	1.	Only use the provided canon.
	2.	Reason from source language first when available.
	3.	Cite relevant passages.
	4.	Distinguish explicit statements from synthesis.
	5.	Present alternate readings when support exists.
	6.	State uncertainty when warranted.
	7.	Translate only after reasoning is complete.
	8.	Never present a generated answer as infallible divine speech.

⸻

Best Use Cases

It is strong for:
	•	scripture study
	•	sermon prep
	•	thematic exploration
	•	interfaith comparison
	•	devotional reflection with citations
	•	doctrinal mapping
	•	root word analysis
	•	self-contained canon synthesis

It is weaker for:
	•	historical reconstruction outside the text
	•	denominational legal rulings
	•	sacramental authority
	•	pastoral care requiring human discernment
	•	community-specific religious practice

⸻

Best Framing

The strongest honest framing is:

The Scripture Engine is a canon-constrained reasoning lens that generates the most text-supported answer available from a selected sacred corpus, with full traceability and uncertainty disclosure.

Not:

a machine that tells you exactly what God thinks.

That second sentence is what breaks the integrity.

The first one is strong enough.

⸻

Pantheon Translation

In Pantheon terms:
	•	Canon = boundary field
	•	Source language = high-fidelity signal layer
	•	Synthesis = bounded meaning extraction
	•	Translation = render layer
	•	Confidence + alternatives = Mirror safeguard
	•	Traceability = Sieve integrity
	•	No oracle claims = ethical checksum

So the Scripture Engine is basically:

a sacred-corpus node with hard boundaries, visible ambiguity, and delayed translation.

